#article_wine.modal_article.modal.fade(tabindex='-1', role='dialog')
  .modal-dialog(role='document')
    .modal-content
      .modal-header
        button.close(type='button', data-dismiss='modal', aria-label='Close')
          span(aria-hidden='true') &times;
        //- button
        h4.modal-title.text-center
        //- h4
      //- modal-header
      .modal-body
        //- h3.text-center Why Wine Doesn't Make You Fat
        img.img-responsive.center-block(src='assets/images/tmp/post_4_thumb.png')
        br
        article
          p Women who drink wine are actually less likely to gain weight than those who are teetotal, according to a new report.
          p Researchers found that regular moderate female drinkers were less likely to become obese after a 13 year study of more than 19,000 women.
          p The finding seems to contradict received dietary wisdom which has it that alcohol consumption leads to weight gain.
          p The body may use calories from alcohol in a different way from other foods which affects weight gain, doctors said.
          p It is thought that alcohol is broken down by the liver using a different metabolic pathway to create heat, rather than fat.
          p Lu Wang, from Brigham and Women's hospital in Boston questioned 19,220 American women with healthy body weight about their drinking habits.
          p About 38 per cent were non-alcohol drinkers. Over 13 years this was the group that gained the most weight.
          p The more women drank the less weight they gained. Those who drank red wine gained the least weight with greater weight gain associated with beer and spirits.
          p The report, published in the Archives of Internal Medicine, said there was no clear connection between alcohol consumption and weight gain.
          p However, Catherine Collins, a spokesman for the British Dietetic Association, said women should not look on wine as a weight loss aid.
          p She said: "If these women have a healthy diet and lifestyle and are having one or two units of alcohol a night then that has less calories than someone who instead has a chocolate bar to unwind. It's a question of "what's your poison?"
          p "Of course if women were drinking more than two units a day they would put on weight. What this survey shows is that moderation is key to a healthy lifestyle. People who drink wine may be more likely to snack on sugary and more calorific treats."
          p The benefits of drinking red wine have already been documented.
          p A study by Barts, the London School of Medicine and the Queen Mary University in London highlighted a mechanism in red wine that appeared to interfere with a body chemical responsible for clogging up the arteries.
          p Research by the Institute of Preventive Medicine in Copenhagen showed that a daily glass of red wine increased good cholesterol by up to 16 per cent, and reduced the clotting compound fibrinogen by up to 15 per cent.
          p Meanwhile, white wine has also been shown to have some beneficial effects, with a 2008 study by the University of Buffalo suggesting that while both red and white wine can bolster lung function, white wine seems to have a more positive effect.
        //- article
      //- modal-body
      .modal-footer
        .text-center
          button.btn.btn-success.btn-lg(type='button', data-dismiss='modal') Done
